Fitch Ratings expects the TTM institutional term loan default rate to finish higher for the ninth consecutive month, potentially reaching 4.6% from 4.3% at August end. September volume registers a modest $1 billion thus far, with filings from iQor US Inc. and Town Sports International Inc., though there could be another $3.5 billion coming. Travelport LLC’s sizable distressed debt exchange (DDE) along with J Jill Group’s restructuring and filings from Chief Power LLC and FTS International Inc. are names to watch. The default pace has certainly slowed from the $9.6 billion monthly average occurring over April through July, but activity is expected to remain elevated throughout the year and into 2021. In March, Fitch projected a two-year cumulative base case default of about 15% by YE 2021, with 5%–6% forecast for YE 2020. We expect the default rate to finish the year at the lower end of our base case range. The YTD default rate is 3.7% on $53.2 billion of volume. It would take another $19 billion to reach 5%. https://www.fitchratings.com/research/corporate-finance/fitch-us-leveraged-loan-default-insight-default-rate-to-rise-ninth-straight-month-top-loans-of-concern-total-increases-18-09-2020

Many factors involved in this so I'm mostly basing this on gut and what happened in 2009. In my mind the biggest factor is that the government response to the pandemic has been good. The FED lowered rates and made loans available quickly, the CARES act seemed to provide good assistance for businesses. I'd guess the climb in leverage loan default will be slower than we saw in 2008 and 2009 for this reason, and it's possible (if the government continues to play an effective role) that these default rates don't exceed 6%. I'd guess they probably will, but I think there's good reason to believe it won't shoot up as fast as in the last recession.

This to me appears to still be moving slowly. If you look at the revised May to June numbers, we’re on track to hit about 5% this year. Also, most of the loans that defaulted in April and May of this year were from companies that were in trouble prior to COVID.

My two rationals here is the Federal Reserve intervention with the direct purchases of bonds will have some cushioning until the end of the year, second we are looking at a growth of defaults of 80% from here in 6 months, things are not great but they're not that grim. YET! If we get to 6% that fast, you better tight your belt and secure it. The Fed time frame has some "hope" baked in the equation. It seems, the Fed has stopped buying, it could be due to some defaults showing in their holdings and before it becomes and issue they need to asses the next round of liquidity. The rational to stop liquidity two weeks already, starts to affect the curve of the balance sheet.

Before beginning my analysis, I must admit that getting a handle on the timing element of the question has been quite difficult. It's really tempting to substitute the question asked for the much easier "Is the credit market in dire straits right now?" I don't think it takes a veteran bond trader to know that many companies are tetering on the brink of collapse. Default rates are through the roof: 33% in the oil and gas sector and 172% ahead of pace overall based on data from the previous period. [1] But despite these scary numbers, there doesn't seem to be an obvious linear relationship in default rates. In fact, it seems to be the exact opposite in some cases. According to a Thomson Reuters analysis of data published tby the credit rating agency Fitch, the default rate declined in the first three months of the year before skyrocketing in April and May. [2]

As of 28 June 2020, Chesapeake Energy Corp. filed for Chapter 11 for defaulting on a revolving credit facility, of which I don't know whether it is some kind of leveraged loan, "the Company will continue to operate its business as 'debtors-in-possession'" in order to enable restructuring financing. A new "Exit Revolving Facility" will be granted. The company had debt of 7.4bn USD on their eoy 2018 balance sheet, but this specific revolving credit will be less than 1bn USD, maybe around 800mn USD of size. It is yet to be seen whether this default will affect other, or all, of the company's credit facilities. It will be interesting to watch, how and when this first default during the lifetime of the question will feed into the index.

April was still below average but higher than April of last year. May remained close. At its highest, the default rate 10 years ago was well below 6%. I am assuming time to accumulate based on the rolling average. https://www.spglobal.com/marketintelligence/en/news-insights/latest-news-headlines/in-grim-sign-us-leveraged-loan-defaults-set-record-in-april-58437664

Don't know much about this topic, but using question data since March 31, linear growth suggests we wouldn't reach 6% until late January; exponential growth suggests late October. But these things can change fast (I found the chart at the bottom of this article [2] helpful to understand the speed of change during Great Recession), so I'm starting by eyeballing with a good amount of uncertainty.
